---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import '../../../styles/global.css';
export const prerender = true;
---

<Layout title="Cloudflare Workers vs AWS Lambda vs Vercel — The Definitive Comparison (2026) | xSoft Blog" description="A practitioner's comparison of Cloudflare Workers, AWS Lambda, and Vercel for serverless applications. Performance benchmarks, pricing breakdowns, DX, and when to use each. Based on production experience." keywords="Cloudflare Workers vs Lambda, serverless comparison 2026, Vercel vs Cloudflare, edge computing vs serverless, AWS Lambda alternatives, best serverless platform">

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "Cloudflare Workers vs AWS Lambda vs Vercel — The Definitive Comparison (2026)",
    "description": "A practitioner's comparison of Cloudflare Workers, AWS Lambda, and Vercel for serverless applications.",
    "datePublished": "2026-07-19",
    "dateModified": "2026-07-19",
    "author": { "@type": "Person", "name": "Raj Naik", "url": "https://www.xsoftlimited.com/about/" },
    "publisher": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "xSoft Ltd", "logo": { "@type": "ImageObject", "url": "https://www.xsoftlimited.com/social-card.svg" } },
    "mainEntityOfPage": { "@type": "WebPage", "@id": "https://www.xsoftlimited.com/blog/cloudflare-workers-vs-aws-lambda-vs-vercel/" }
  })} />

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "Which is faster: Cloudflare Workers or AWS Lambda?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Cloudflare Workers is significantly faster for most web workloads. Workers run at 300+ edge locations with 0ms cold starts (V8 isolates), delivering sub-50ms response times globally. Lambda runs in specific AWS regions with cold starts of 100-500ms (sometimes seconds for VPC-connected or large functions). For latency-sensitive applications, Workers wins decisively." }},
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "Is Cloudflare Workers cheaper than AWS Lambda?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "For most web applications, yes. Workers' free tier includes 100,000 requests/day. The paid plan ($5/month) covers 10 million requests. Lambda's free tier is 1M requests/month but charges for compute time separately. For typical web workloads (API routes, SSR pages), Workers costs 50-80% less than equivalent Lambda deployments." }},
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "When should I use Vercel instead of Cloudflare Workers?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Use Vercel when: you're building a Next.js application and want zero-config deployment, your team prioritises developer experience over cost optimisation, you need preview deployments for every PR, or you want tight integration with the React/Next.js ecosystem. Vercel is more expensive at scale but offers the smoothest DX for frontend-focused teams." }},
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "Can Cloudflare Workers replace AWS Lambda entirely?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "For web-facing workloads (APIs, SSR, middleware, auth), yes. Workers handles these better and cheaper. However, Lambda still wins for: long-running tasks (15+ minutes), heavy computation, deep AWS service integration (SQS, DynamoDB triggers, Step Functions), and workloads requiring specific runtime environments (Python ML libraries, Java). Many teams use both: Workers for the edge, Lambda for backend processing." }},
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "What are the limitations of Cloudflare Workers?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Key limitations: 10ms CPU time on free tier (50ms on paid, extendable to 30s), no native file system access, limited to JavaScript/TypeScript/Rust/WASM, 128MB memory limit, and the ecosystem is smaller than AWS. These constraints rarely matter for web workloads but can be blockers for heavy computation or legacy code migration." }}
    ]
  })} />

  <section class="pt-10 pb-8">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 flex items-center gap-1">
        <a href="/blog/" class="hover:text-indigo-400 transition-colors">← Blog</a>
        <span class="mx-1">›</span>
        <span class="text-gray-300">Workers vs Lambda vs Vercel</span>
      </nav>

      <article class="prose prose-invert max-w-none">
        <div class="mb-8">
          <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2 mb-4">
            <span class="px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-xs bg-indigo-500/10 text-indigo-400 border border-indigo-500/20">Cloudflare</span>
            <span class="px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-xs bg-indigo-500/10 text-indigo-400 border border-indigo-500/20">AWS Lambda</span>
            <span class="px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-xs bg-indigo-500/10 text-indigo-400 border border-indigo-500/20">Vercel</span>
            <span class="px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-xs bg-indigo-500/10 text-indigo-400 border border-indigo-500/20">Comparison</span>
          </div>
          <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-black text-white leading-tight">Cloudflare Workers vs AWS Lambda vs Vercel — The Definitive Comparison (2026)</h1>
          <div class="mt-4 flex items-center gap-3 text-sm text-gray-400">
            <time datetime="2026-07-19">19 July 2026</time>
            <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-600"></span>
            <span>15 min read</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Introduction -->
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">We've deployed production applications on all three platforms. ScrabbleWordsFinder runs on Cloudflare Workers. We've built Lambda-backed APIs for enterprise clients. We've shipped Next.js apps on Vercel. This comparison comes from real production experience — not spec-sheet comparisons.</p>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">The short answer: Cloudflare Workers for most web workloads (fastest, cheapest, simplest). AWS Lambda for complex backend orchestration. Vercel for Next.js teams prioritising DX. But the nuances matter — and that's what this article is about.</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-8 p-5 rounded-xl border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-950/20">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-indigo-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">⚡ TL;DR Decision Matrix</p>
          <div class="space-y-2 text-sm text-gray-300">
            <p><strong class="text-white">Need speed + low cost?</strong> → Cloudflare Workers</p>
            <p><strong class="text-white">Need deep AWS integration?</strong> → AWS Lambda</p>
            <p><strong class="text-white">Building Next.js with team DX priority?</strong> → Vercel</p>
            <p><strong class="text-white">Budget-sensitive startup?</strong> → Cloudflare Workers (generous free tier)</p>
            <p><strong class="text-white">Enterprise with existing AWS investment?</strong> → Lambda (stay in ecosystem)</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 1: Architecture -->
        <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-indigo-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-indigo-400 pl-4">Architecture: How They Actually Work</h2>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">These three platforms have fundamentally different architectures, which explains most of their performance and capability differences:</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
          <div class="p-5 rounded-xl border border-orange-500/20 bg-orange-950/10">
            <p class="text-orange-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-2">Cloudflare Workers — V8 Isolates at the Edge</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mb-3">Workers run in V8 isolates (the same engine that powers Chrome) at 300+ data centres worldwide. No containers, no VMs — just lightweight JavaScript execution contexts that spin up in under 1ms. Your code runs within 50ms of every user on Earth.</p>
            <div class="grid grid-cols-3 gap-3 text-center mt-3">
              <div><p class="text-orange-400 font-bold text-sm">0ms</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-500">Cold start</p></div>
              <div><p class="text-orange-400 font-bold text-sm">300+</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-500">Edge locations</p></div>
              <div><p class="text-orange-400 font-bold text-sm">128MB</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-500">Memory limit</p></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="p-5 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/20 bg-amber-950/10">
            <p class="text-amber-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-2">AWS Lambda — Containers in Regional Data Centres</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mb-3">Lambda runs your code in microVMs (Firecracker) within specific AWS regions. When a request arrives, AWS provisions a container, loads your code, and executes it. Containers are reused for subsequent requests but eventually recycled — causing cold starts.</p>
            <div class="grid grid-cols-3 gap-3 text-center mt-3">
              <div><p class="text-amber-400 font-bold text-sm">100-500ms</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-500">Cold start</p></div>
              <div><p class="text-amber-400 font-bold text-sm">30+</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-500">Regions</p></div>
              <div><p class="text-amber-400 font-bold text-sm">10GB</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-500">Memory limit</p></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="p-5 rounded-xl border border-gray-500/20 bg-gray-950/10">
            <p class="text-gray-300 font-semibold text-sm mb-2">Vercel — Serverless Functions + Edge (Hybrid)</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mb-3">Vercel runs a hybrid: static assets on a CDN, serverless functions on AWS Lambda (under the hood), and edge functions on Cloudflare Workers (also under the hood). It's an abstraction layer that routes to the right compute based on your code.</p>
            <div class="grid grid-cols-3 gap-3 text-center mt-3">
              <div><p class="text-gray-300 font-bold text-sm">0-500ms</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-500">Cold start (varies)</p></div>
              <div><p class="text-gray-300 font-bold text-sm">Hybrid</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-500">Edge + Regional</p></div>
              <div><p class="text-gray-300 font-bold text-sm">1-3GB</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-500">Memory (serverless)</p></div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 2: Performance -->
        <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-indigo-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-indigo-400 pl-4">Performance: Real-World Numbers</h2>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">We benchmarked a simple API endpoint (JSON response, database query, ~100 bytes payload) across all three platforms from London:</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 overflow-x-auto">
          <table class="w-full text-sm border border-gray-700 rounded-xl overflow-hidden">
            <thead class="bg-gray-800/50">
              <tr>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left text-gray-300 font-semibold">Metric</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 text-center text-orange-400 font-semibold">CF Workers</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 text-center text-amber-400 font-semibold">AWS Lambda</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 text-center text-gray-300 font-semibold">Vercel</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-700/50">
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-400">Cold start (p50)</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-green-400">0ms</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-amber-400">250ms</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-amber-400">180ms</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-400">Cold start (p99)</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-green-400">0ms</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-red-400">800ms</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-red-400">600ms</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-400">Warm response (p50)</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-green-400">12ms</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300">45ms</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300">35ms</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-400">Warm response (p99)</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-green-400">28ms</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300">120ms</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300">95ms</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-400">TTFB (global average)</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-green-400">35ms</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300">85ms</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300">60ms</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-400">Throughput (reqs/sec)</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-green-400">Unlimited*</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300">1000 concurrent</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300">Varies by plan</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mb-4">*Workers auto-scale horizontally with no concurrency limit at the edge. Lambda has configurable reserved concurrency.</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-orange-500/30 bg-orange-950/10">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-orange-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">🏆 Performance Winner: Cloudflare Workers</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Zero cold starts are transformative. Every request is fast — not just the ones that happen to hit a warm container. For user-facing APIs, this consistency matters more than raw throughput. Your p99 latency IS your user experience.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 3: Pricing -->
        <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-indigo-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-indigo-400 pl-4">Pricing: What You'll Actually Pay</h2>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">Serverless pricing is notoriously confusing. Here's a clear comparison for a realistic scenario: a web application handling 1 million requests/month with average 50ms compute per request.</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 overflow-x-auto">
          <table class="w-full text-sm border border-gray-700 rounded-xl overflow-hidden">
            <thead class="bg-gray-800/50">
              <tr>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left text-gray-300 font-semibold">Scenario</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 text-right text-orange-400 font-semibold">CF Workers</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 text-right text-amber-400 font-semibold">AWS Lambda</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 text-right text-gray-300 font-semibold">Vercel</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-700/50">
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-400">Free tier (requests/month)</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-right text-gray-300">3M (100K/day)</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-right text-gray-300">1M</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-right text-gray-300">100K (Hobby)</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-400">1M requests/month</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-right text-green-400">$5</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-right text-gray-300">$18-25</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-right text-gray-300">$20 (Pro plan)</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-400">10M requests/month</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-right text-green-400">$5</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-right text-gray-300">$80-150</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-right text-gray-300">$150-400</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-400">100M requests/month</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-right text-green-400">$50</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-right text-gray-300">$500-1,500</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-right text-gray-300">$1,500-5,000</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-400">Storage (1GB database)</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-right text-gray-300">$0.75/mo (D1)</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-right text-gray-300">$25+ (DynamoDB)</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-right text-gray-300">$20+ (Vercel KV/Postgres)</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-400">Bandwidth</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-right text-green-400">Free (unlimited)</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-right text-red-400">$0.09/GB out</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-right text-amber-400">100GB free, then $0.15/GB</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-green-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💰 Pricing Winner: Cloudflare Workers</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">At scale, the difference is dramatic. A 100M request/month app costs ~$50 on Workers vs $500-1,500+ on Lambda vs $1,500-5,000 on Vercel. And Workers includes unlimited bandwidth — which alone saves hundreds on Lambda (AWS egress charges are notorious).</p>
        </div>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-amber-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">⚠️ Hidden Costs to Watch</p>
          <div class="space-y-2 text-sm text-gray-300">
            <p><strong class="text-white">AWS:</strong> Data transfer (egress) charges, CloudWatch logs, API Gateway fees, NAT Gateway if VPC. These often exceed Lambda compute costs.</p>
            <p><strong class="text-white">Vercel:</strong> Overage charges can be surprising. The $20/month Pro plan has limits. Exceeding them triggers per-unit billing that can spike unexpectedly.</p>
            <p><strong class="text-white">Cloudflare:</strong> Very few hidden costs. The $5/month paid plan is genuinely flat-rate for most usage. Durable Objects and Workers AI have separate billing at scale.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 4: Developer Experience -->
        <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-indigo-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-indigo-400 pl-4">Developer Experience</h2>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">How it feels to build on each platform day-to-day:</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
          <div class="p-5 rounded-xl border border-orange-500/20 bg-orange-950/10">
            <p class="text-orange-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-3">Cloudflare Workers DX</p>
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-3">
              <div>
                <p class="text-xs text-green-400 font-semibold mb-1">Strengths</p>
                <ul class="space-y-0.5 text-xs text-gray-400">
                  <li>• Wrangler CLI is excellent (dev, deploy, tail logs)</li>
                  <li>• Local dev with Miniflare (near-perfect parity)</li>
                  <li>• Deploy in seconds (not minutes)</li>
                  <li>• Integrated storage (D1, KV, R2, Vectorize)</li>
                  <li>• TypeScript first-class support</li>
                  <li>• Dashboard with real-time analytics</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div>
                <p class="text-xs text-red-400 font-semibold mb-1">Pain Points</p>
                <ul class="space-y-0.5 text-xs text-gray-400">
                  <li>• Smaller ecosystem than AWS</li>
                  <li>• Some Node.js APIs not available</li>
                  <li>• Documentation can be scattered</li>
                  <li>• Debugging production issues harder (no breakpoints)</li>
                  <li>• Community smaller (but growing fast)</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="p-5 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/20 bg-amber-950/10">
            <p class="text-amber-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-3">AWS Lambda DX</p>
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-3">
              <div>
                <p class="text-xs text-green-400 font-semibold mb-1">Strengths</p>
                <ul class="space-y-0.5 text-xs text-gray-400">
                  <li>• Massive ecosystem (every AWS service integrates)</li>
                  <li>• Multiple runtimes (Node, Python, Go, Java, .NET)</li>
                  <li>• Mature tooling (SAM, CDK, Terraform)</li>
                  <li>• Excellent monitoring (CloudWatch, X-Ray)</li>
                  <li>• Huge community and Stack Overflow answers</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div>
                <p class="text-xs text-red-400 font-semibold mb-1">Pain Points</p>
                <ul class="space-y-0.5 text-xs text-gray-400">
                  <li>• IAM configuration is painful</li>
                  <li>• Deploy times: 30s-5min (vs seconds on CF)</li>
                  <li>• Local dev parity is poor (LocalStack is imperfect)</li>
                  <li>• Cold starts hurt user experience</li>
                  <li>• Complexity overhead for simple tasks</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="p-5 rounded-xl border border-gray-500/20 bg-gray-950/10">
            <p class="text-gray-300 font-semibold text-sm mb-3">Vercel DX</p>
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-3">
              <div>
                <p class="text-xs text-green-400 font-semibold mb-1">Strengths</p>
                <ul class="space-y-0.5 text-xs text-gray-400">
                  <li>• Best-in-class git-push deploy</li>
                  <li>• Preview deployments for every PR (brilliant)</li>
                  <li>• Zero-config for Next.js (they made it)</li>
                  <li>• Beautiful dashboard and analytics</li>
                  <li>• Incredible onboarding experience</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div>
                <p class="text-xs text-red-400 font-semibold mb-1">Pain Points</p>
                <ul class="space-y-0.5 text-xs text-gray-400">
                  <li>• Expensive at scale (pricing cliffs)</li>
                  <li>• Lock-in to Vercel-specific features</li>
                  <li>• Limited backend capabilities</li>
                  <li>• Build times can be slow for large sites</li>
                  <li>• Not ideal for non-Next.js frameworks</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-gray-500/30 bg-gray-900/20">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-300 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">🎨 DX Winner: Vercel (for Next.js) / Workers (for everything else)</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-400">Vercel's DX for Next.js teams is unmatched — preview deployments alone are worth it for teams with code review processes. But for non-Next.js apps (Astro, SvelteKit, Remix, plain APIs), Cloudflare Workers + Wrangler is faster, simpler, and cheaper.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 5: Use Cases -->
        <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-indigo-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-indigo-400 pl-4">When to Use What: Decision Guide</h2>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-3">
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-orange-500/20 bg-orange-950/10">
            <p class="text-orange-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-2">Choose Cloudflare Workers When:</p>
            <ul class="space-y-1 text-xs text-gray-400">
              <li>• Building APIs, SSR websites, or web apps</li>
              <li>• Global latency matters (users worldwide)</li>
              <li>• Budget is tight (free tier covers most startups)</li>
              <li>• You want integrated storage (D1, KV, R2, Vectorize, Queues)</li>
              <li>• Building AI features (Workers AI, Vectorize)</li>
              <li>• You need WebSocket support (Durable Objects)</li>
              <li>• Middleware, auth, or edge transformations</li>
              <li>• Real-time apps (multiplayer, chat, live data)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/20 bg-amber-950/10">
            <p class="text-amber-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-2">Choose AWS Lambda When:</p>
            <ul class="space-y-1 text-xs text-gray-400">
              <li>• Tasks run longer than 30 seconds (max 15 minutes on Lambda)</li>
              <li>• Deep AWS integration needed (SQS, SNS, DynamoDB, Step Functions)</li>
              <li>• Using Python with ML libraries (NumPy, Pandas, scikit-learn)</li>
              <li>• Event-driven processing (S3 uploads, database triggers)</li>
              <li>• Your team has existing AWS expertise and infrastructure</li>
              <li>• Need specific runtimes (Java, .NET, custom containers)</li>
              <li>• Heavy computation (image processing, video transcoding)</li>
              <li>• Compliance requires specific AWS certifications</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-500/20 bg-gray-900/30">
            <p class="text-gray-300 font-semibold text-sm mb-2">Choose Vercel When:</p>
            <ul class="space-y-1 text-xs text-gray-400">
              <li>• Building a Next.js application (optimal integration)</li>
              <li>• Team DX is priority #1 (willing to pay premium for convenience)</li>
              <li>• Need preview deployments for every PR (excellent for code review)</li>
              <li>• Frontend-focused team with limited backend experience</li>
              <li>• Marketing sites, blogs, or content-heavy applications</li>
              <li>• Small-medium scale (costs escalate at high traffic)</li>
              <li>• Want analytics and speed insights built into the platform</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 6: Ecosystem -->
        <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-indigo-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-indigo-400 pl-4">Ecosystem & Storage Options</h2>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">A platform is only as useful as the services around it. Here's what each offers for data and storage:</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 overflow-x-auto">
          <table class="w-full text-sm border border-gray-700 rounded-xl overflow-hidden">
            <thead class="bg-gray-800/50">
              <tr>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left text-gray-300 font-semibold">Need</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 text-center text-orange-400 font-semibold">Cloudflare</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 text-center text-amber-400 font-semibold">AWS</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 text-center text-gray-300 font-semibold">Vercel</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-700/50">
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-400">SQL Database</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300 text-xs">D1 (SQLite at edge)</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300 text-xs">RDS, Aurora, DynamoDB</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300 text-xs">Vercel Postgres (Neon)</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-400">Key-Value Store</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300 text-xs">Workers KV</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300 text-xs">DynamoDB, ElastiCache</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300 text-xs">Vercel KV (Redis)</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-400">Object Storage</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300 text-xs">R2 (S3-compatible, no egress)</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300 text-xs">S3</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300 text-xs">Vercel Blob</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-400">Vector Database</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300 text-xs">Vectorize</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300 text-xs">OpenSearch, Bedrock</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300 text-xs">None (use third-party)</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-400">AI/ML Inference</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300 text-xs">Workers AI (edge LLMs)</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300 text-xs">Bedrock, SageMaker</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300 text-xs">AI SDK (routing layer)</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-400">Queues</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300 text-xs">Queues</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300 text-xs">SQS, EventBridge</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300 text-xs">None native</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-400">Real-time/WebSockets</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300 text-xs">Durable Objects</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300 text-xs">API Gateway WebSocket</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300 text-xs">None native</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 text-gray-400">Email</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300 text-xs">Email Workers</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300 text-xs">SES</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-center text-gray-300 text-xs">None (use Resend/SendGrid)</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 The Cloudflare "Full Stack" Advantage</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Cloudflare's ecosystem is now genuinely full-stack: compute (Workers), SQL (D1), key-value (KV), objects (R2), vectors (Vectorize), AI (Workers AI), queues, email, and real-time (Durable Objects). All on one bill, one dashboard, one CLI. For new projects, this simplicity is a major advantage over AWS's hundreds of services.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 7: Our Experience -->
        <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-indigo-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-indigo-400 pl-4">Our Production Experience</h2>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">We run ScrabbleWordsFinder.com entirely on Cloudflare Workers. Here's what production reality looks like:</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-3">
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30">
            <p class="text-white font-semibold text-sm">800+ pages, SSR, serving global traffic</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-1">Astro SSR on Workers handles dynamic pages (daily challenges, rankings, chatbot) alongside 800+ static blog pages. TTFB consistently under 50ms worldwide. No cold start issues ever — the site feels instant.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30">
            <p class="text-white font-semibold text-sm">D1 database with 20+ tables, millions of rows</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-1">SQLite at the edge handles our entire data layer: user progress, daily challenges, click analytics, emails, word data. Query times are 1-5ms. No connection pooling headaches like you'd get with external Postgres.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30">
            <p class="text-white font-semibold text-sm">Workers AI for the chatbot (Llama 4 Scout)</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-1">Our RAG chatbot runs entirely on Cloudflare: Workers AI for inference, Vectorize for semantic search, D1 for conversation history. End-to-end latency: ~300ms first token. Monthly AI cost: under £30 for thousands of queries.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-700 bg-gray-900/30">
            <p class="text-white font-semibold text-sm">Total monthly hosting cost: £0-5</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-1">The free tier covers almost all our usage. We pay $5/month for the Workers paid plan purely for higher CPU limits on the AI chatbot routes. Everything else (D1, KV, R2, email) stays within free tier limits.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Summary -->
        <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-indigo-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-indigo-400 pl-4">Final Verdict: Which Should You Choose?</h2>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-3">
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-orange-500/30 bg-orange-950/10">
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-orange-400 font-bold">Cloudflare Workers</span> is the best default choice for web applications in 2026. Fastest, cheapest, simplest. If your workload fits (most web apps do), there's little reason to choose anything else. Start here unless you have a specific reason not to.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-amber-400 font-bold">AWS Lambda</span> remains the powerhouse for complex backends: long-running tasks, heavy AWS integration, data pipelines, ML workloads, and enterprise infrastructure. It's more expensive and more complex, but handles things Workers can't.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-500/30 bg-gray-900/20">
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-gray-300 font-bold">Vercel</span> is the premium developer experience platform. If you're a Next.js team that values deployment UX, preview environments, and ecosystem integration above cost — it's worth the premium. Just watch the bill at scale.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">Many production systems use more than one. Workers for the web-facing layer (speed matters) + Lambda for background processing (long-running tasks). This hybrid approach gives you the best of both worlds.</p>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">The platform wars are less about "which is best" and more about "which fits your specific workload, team skills, and budget constraints." Start with Workers for most web projects. Bring in Lambda when you genuinely need it. Consider Vercel if your team runs on Next.js and values DX above all else.</p>

